4. **Main Answer Body**

   | **Aspect**                           | **Discussion**                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              |
   | ------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
   | **Drafting & Historical Background** | • Based on Jawaharlal Nehru’s Objective Resolution (13 Dec 1946).<br>• Debated over three years; adopted unanimously (26 Nov 1949) to reflect collective aspirations (Shukla).                                                                                                                              |
   | **Non-Justiciable Character**        | • No Article number; cannot be invoked directly to enforce rights.<br>• Holds moral and directive force rather than operative legal effect (Jain).                                                                                                                                                          |
   | **Part of Basic Structure**          | • *Kesavananda Bharati* placed Preamble values (e.g., democracy, secularism, socialism) beyond Parliament’s amending power (Art. 368).<br>• Any amendment eroding these ideals is ultra vires (Shukla; Jain).                                                                                               |
   | **Interpretative Aid**               | • Courts routinely refer to the Preamble to resolve textual ambiguities.<br>• In *Maneka Gandhi v. Union of India* (1978), “liberty” under Art. 21 was expansively interpreted in light of Preamble guarantees.<br>• Ensures harmonious construction of Fundamental Rights and Directive Principles (Jain). |
